title: Outstanding projects commended at health promotion symposium (with photos)
content_text:
p>
	Ten health promotion projects were commended at the Health Promotion 
	Symposium 2015 organised by the Research Office of the Food and Health 
	Bureau (FHB) today (November 20), in recognition of their outstanding 
	contributions to health promotion and disease prevention. These projects, funded by the Health Care and Promotion Fund (HCPF) under 
	the FHB, cover a wide range of health topics, including tobacco control, 
	healthy diet, physical exercise, mental health, injury prevention, parenting

healthy diet, physical exercise, mental health, injury prevention, parenting 
	and healthy ageing. Under the theme "Dissemination and Implementation Science in Health 
	Promotion", the Health Promotion Symposium presented a fine selection of 
	excellent projects supported by the HCPF and showcased their outcomes in the 
	parallel sessions and poster exhibition. Officiating at the opening ceremony of the symposium, the Secretary for Food 
	and Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, said this year's symposium highlighted the

and Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, said this year's symposium highlighted the 
	importance of evidence-based practices in health promotion. "For health promotion interventions to be effective and sustainable, a 
	collaborative partnership among stakeholders is imperative. Tobacco control 
	is one of the successful examples to demonstrate the effectiveness in 
	translating accumulated evidence and efforts into health policy," he said. Bringing together academics, healthcare professionals, and government and 
	non-governmental organisation representatives, the symposium served as a 
	platform for stakeholders to network and collaborate. An internationally

platform for stakeholders to network and collaborate. An internationally renowned public health expert, Professor Alice Ammerman from the University of North Carolina, delivered a keynote lecture on the theme of the symposium. The 10 special awards presented at the symposium today are as follows: Outstanding Health Promotion Project Award:
Professor Alfred Chan
Dr Angela Leung
Professor Agnes Tiwari
Professor Wong Sze-chun
Ms Sania Yau Excellent Health Promotion Project Award:

Ms Sania Yau Excellent Health Promotion Project Award:
Dr Chow Chun-bong
Ms Lau Pik-shan
Professor Vivian Lee
Ms Mariana Wong
Ms Yu Siu-wan Ends/Friday, November 20, 2015
